#pods

kubectl get pods/pod/po: Lists all running and pending pods in the current Kubernetes namespace, showing their names, status, number of restarts, and age
kubectl get pods --show-labels: Lists all pods in the current namespace and displays their associated labels, helping you identify or filter pods based on label metadata
kubectl label pod pod-1 Env=Dev: Adds or updates the label Env=Dev on the pod named pod-1, which can be used for organization, selection, or filtering of Kubernetes resources
kubectl get pod -l app=Zomato:(Set Based Selector) Lists all pods in the current namespace that have the label app=Zomato, allowing you to filter resources based on labels
kubectl get pods --show-labels | grep '<none>': Lists all pods that do not have any labels assigned, by showing labels for all pods and filtering for entries with <none>
kubectl get po -l 'Env in (Test, Dev)':(Equality Based Selector) Lists all pods that have the label Env set to either Test or Dev, allowing selection of multiple label values using the in operator
kubectl get nodes/node/no: Displays the list of Kubernetes cluster nodes along with their status, roles, age, and version
kubectl run pod_name --image=image_name: Creates a new pod in Kubernetes using the specified image, generating a single-container pod with the given name
kubectl api-resources: Displays all Kubernetes resource types supported by the cluster’s API, including their short names, API groups, whether they are namespaced, and their resource kinds
kubectl create -f podcreation.yml: Creates Kubernetes resources (such as Pods, Deployments, Services, etc.) defined inside the podcreation.yml file
kubectl apply -f manifest_file.yml → Creates or updates Kubernetes resources defined in the specified YAML manifest file, applying any changes without deleting existing configurations
kubectl get po pod_name: Displays the status and details of a specific pod by name, including its phase, age, and restart count
kubectl get po pod_name -o wide: Shows detailed information about the specified pod, including its node assignment, pod IP, container images, and other extended metadata beyond the default output
kubectl get po pod_name -o yaml: Displays the complete YAML representation of the specified pod, including metadata, specification, and current status
kubectl get po pod_name -o json: Displays the complete JSON representation of the specified pod, including metadata, spec, and current status
kubectl get po -o wide: Lists all pods in the current namespace with extended details such as pod IPs, node names, and container images
kubectl get po -o yaml: Outputs all pod definitions in the current namespace in YAML format, showing full configuration details such as metadata, spec, and status
kubectl get po -o json: Outputs all pods in the current namespace in JSON format, showing full configuration details including metadata, spec, and status
kubectl describe pod pod_name: Displays detailed information about the specified pod, including its containers, events, status, resource usage, node assignment, and any errors or warnings
kubectl delete pod pod_name: Deletes the specified pod from the Kubernetes cluster. The pod’s containers are terminated, and its resources are freed
kubectl delete pod --all: Deletes all pods in the current namespace, terminating their containers and freeing associated resources


kubectl get svc: Lists all services in the current Kubernetes namespace, showing their names, types (ClusterIP, NodePort, LoadBalancer), cluster IPs, external IPs, ports, and age
kubectl delete svc svc_name: Deletes the specified service from the Kubernetes cluster, removing its network endpoints and stopping external access to the associated pods
kubectl delete svc --all: Deletes all services in the current namespace, removing their network endpoints and stopping external access to the associated pods

#ReplicationController- Self healing Pods
kubectl get rc: Lists all ReplicationControllers in the current namespace, showing their names, desired vs. current replicas, and age
kubectl describe rc rc_name: Shows detailed information about the specified ReplicationController, including its labels, selector, replica count, pod template, and recent events
kubectl delete rc rc_name: Deletes the specified ReplicationController, which will also terminate the pods it manages unless they are orphaned with additional flags
kubectl delete rc rc_name --cascade=orphan: Deletes the specified ReplicationController but keeps its pods running by orphaning them, meaning they will no longer be managed or monitored by the RC
kubectl scale rc rc_name --replicas 5: Scales the specified ReplicationController to 5 replicas, ensuring it runs five pod instances

kubectl get rs: Lists all ReplicaSets in the current namespace, showing their names, desired/current/ready replicas, and age

kubectl get deployment: Lists all Deployments in the current namespace, showing their names, desired and current replica counts, available pods, and age
kubectl set image deployment/deployment_name container_name=image_name: Updates image for the specified container in a Deployment, triggering a rolling update of the pods managed by that Deployment
kubectl rollout history deployment/deployment_name: Shows the revision history of the specified Deployment, including previous versions of the Deployment configuration and container images
kubectl rollout undo deployment/deployment_name --to-revision=1: Reverts the specified Deployment to a previous revision (here, revision 1), restoring the Deployment’s pods to the state of that revision
kubectl rollout status deployment/deployment_name: Displays the current rollout status of the specified Deployment, showing whether the update is complete, in progress, or has failed
kubectl rollout pause deployment/deployment_name: Pauses the rollout of the specified Deployment, preventing new updates from being applied to its pods until the rollout is resumed
kubectl rollout resume deployment/deployment_name: Resumes a previously paused Deployment rollout, allowing updates to continue and new pods to be deployed according to the Deployment specification

kubectl get hpa: Lists all Horizontal Pod Autoscalers in the current namespace, showing their target workloads, replica ranges, current metrics, and scaling status
kubectl get hpa -w: Continuously watches and displays live updates of all Horizontal Pod Autoscalers, showing real-time changes in metrics and replica counts
kubectl exec -it pod_name -- bash: Opens an interactive bash shell inside the specified pod, allowing you to run commands directly inside the container

kubectl get ds: Lists all DaemonSets in the current namespace, showing their names, desired/current/ready pod counts, and age
kubectl delete ds daemon_name: Deletes the specified DaemonSet, which also removes all pods managed by that DaemonSet across cluster nodes
kubectl describe ds daemon_name: Shows detailed information about the specified DaemonSet, including its pod template, node selectors, update strategy, events, and the status of pods running on each node

kubectl get ns: Lists all namespaces in the Kubernetes cluster, showing their names and current status
kubectl create ns namespace: (Imperative)Creates a new Kubernetes namespace with the specified name, providing a separate environment for organizing and isolating resources
kubectl delete ns namespace: Deletes the specified Kubernetes namespace along with all resources (pods, services, deployments, etc.) contained within it
kubectl run pod_name --image=image_name -n namespace_name: Creates a new pod in the given namespace, instead of the default namespace
kubectl create -f pod.yml -n namespace_name: Creates a pod (or other Kubernetes resource) from the pod.yml manifest file inside the specified namespace
kubectl get po -n namespace_name: Lists all pods in the specified namespace, showing their names, statuses, restarts, and ages
kubectl config set-context --current --namespace=namespace_name: Sets the default namespace for the current context, so subsequent kubectl commands will automatically operate within that namespace without needing the -n flag


kubectl exec -it pod1_name -c cont-2 -- bash: Opens an interactive Bash shell inside the container cont-2 of the specified pod
kubectl get pv: Lists all PersistentVolumes (PVs) in the cluster, showing their capacity, access modes, reclaim policy, status, claim, storage class, and age
kubectl get pvc: Lists all PersistentVolumeClaims (PVCs) in the current namespace, showing their status, volume bound, capacity, access modes, storage class, and age
kubectl describe pvc pvc_name: Displays detailed information about a specific PersistentVolumeClaim, including its status, events, requested storage, access modes, bound PersistentVolume, and conditions


kubectl create cm configmap_name --from-literal Name=Balaji --from-literal College=SETU --from-literal Course=DevOps:
   Creates a ConfigMap named configmap_name using key–value pairs provided directly in the command.Useful for storing non-confidential configuration data for pods (Imperative Way-Literal)
kubectl get cm: Lists all ConfigMaps in the current namespace, showing their names and ages
kubectl describe cm cm_name: Displays detailed information about the specified ConfigMap, including:Key–value pairs stored in it, Namespace, Labels & annotations, Events
kubectl create cm configmap_name --from-file=file_name: Creates a ConfigMap from a file, where the filename becomes the key and the file contents become the value (Imperative Way-File)
kubectl create cm configmap_name --from-env-file=filename.env: Creates a ConfigMap from a .env file, where each KEY=VALUE pair in the file becomes a separate entry in the ConfigMap (Imperative Way-EnvFile)
kubectl create cm configmap_name --from-file=folder_name: Creates a ConfigMap from an entire folder, where each file inside the folder becomes a key, and the content of each file becomes the value for that key (Imperative Way-Folder)


kubectl get secret: Lists all Secrets in the current namespace, showing their names, types, and ages
kubectl create secret generic secret_name --from-literal=username=balaji07 --from-literal=password=Balaji@2000:
    Creates a generic (encrypted) Secret named secret_name with key-value pairs provided directly in the command

kubectl get resourcequota -n namespace_name: Lists all ResourceQuotas in the specified namespace, showing their names and usage vs limits

kubectl get roles -n namespace_name: Lists all Roles created inside the specific namespace, showing their names, creation time, and labels
kubectl get rolebinding -n namespace_name: Lists all RoleBindings in the specific namespace, showing which users/groups/service accounts are bound to which Roles
kubectl get clusterrole: Lists all ClusterRoles available in the Kubernetes cluster
kubectl get clusterrolebinding: Lists all ClusterRoleBindings in the cluster, showing which users/groups/service accounts are bound to which ClusterRoles

#s3&cluster
aws s3 ls: Lists all S3 buckets in AWS account
aws s3 mb s3://balaji.practice.k8s: Creates a new S3 bucket named balaji.practice.k8s. The mb command stands for make bucket
aws s3 ls s3://balaji.practice.k8s: Lists all objects (files/folders) stored inside the S3 bucket balaji.practice.k8s
export KOPS_STATE_STORE=s3://bucket_name: Sets the environment variable KOPS_STATE_STORE to point to the specified S3 bucket. This bucket is used by kops to store cluster configuration, state, and metadata
kops create cluster --name cluster_name.k8s.local --zones us-east-1a,us-east-1b --master-size t2.medium --master-count 1 --node-size t2.micro --node-count 2:
 Generates the configuration for a Kubernetes cluster managed by kops, specifying: Cluster name (with .k8s.local DNS suffix), Az's, Master node size&count, Worker node size&count. This prepares, but does not yet build, the cluster
kops update cluster --name cluster_name.k8s.local --yes --admin: Applies the cluster configuration and starts creating the Kubernetes cluster
 --yes executes the changes without prompting, --admin generates temporary admin credentials for accessing the cluster
kops get cluster: Lists all Kubernetes clusters managed by kops in the configured KOPS_STATE_STORE, showing their names, cloud provider, and current state
kops delete cluster --name cluster_name_with_extension --yes: Deletes the specified Kubernetes cluster managed by kops, including all associated resources, without prompting for confirmation
